76561198094154627,Not Recommended,410670,20583319,"Posted: 17 January, 2016",all,ryanjames,"Where to start with this game? I wanted to like this game, the artstyle and surreal atmosphere/setting drew me in, having thoroughly enjoyed titles such as undertale and LISA, I imaged I was in for a similar ride. Unfortunately this was not so, this game was generally not very enjoyable, simply due to how it was executed. I'll start off with what I liked first though.If you don't want to read a wall of text, skip to the conclusion at the bottomThe artstyle is, very very interesting, it is something that has drawn alot of people in, it gives the game a unique feel, and enemy sprites were generally interesting to look at, surreal, pen drawn abominations in suits and political cartoons. Secondly, the music is another striking feature of this game. Like the art style, it is very atmospheric, and just fits very well with the setting of the game. There isn't loads of music, but there isn't a lack of it either. Another ""strong"" point of the game is the humour. I have mixed feelings about the humour, I did chuckle at the various references to modern politics and some puns did make me laugh, but at times the humour felt very forced, or just, didn't make any sense. Lastly, there is Jerome. Jerome is good.Now, onto the negative aspects, the first main issue is combat. Combat is extremely simplistic, you only ever have two party members (apparently there is a third somewhere?) with an incredibly simplistic and limited range of abilities. Fights mainly consist of stocking up on sandwichs, and just attacking enemies in a war of endurance. Sandwichs get you through this game, not any strategy. Random encounters are also extremely common and frequent. Secondly, there is plot, the game's plot is apparently a business man's descent into corruption.Well, not really, you complete a couple tasks for your capitalist overlords, and then, police attack you for some reason, and you somehow windup leading a revolution through a series of events that don't make sense. At the end of the game, the last boss decides to drop about 5 bombshells on you with no warning. Everything about the plot is dull, forced and just badly executed. Another strong negative point is the writing in general, again, everything is just forced. Some jokes, as stated did make me laugh, but there's alot of dialogue that, seemed to be a joke, but just wasn't funny. The last thing, is that, it just doesn't feel like there's any point to the game, it's wasted potential. This game is very quirky in some ways, with it's artstyle, curious setting and the fact that all plants have female names. There is potential here to make a really damn good and unique RPG. But this game fails to say anything about politics other than ""Corporations are bad!"" or really make you feel anything. The plot is just a series of events that happen.Oh, one very last point, Jerome should say more, you don't hear a peep from him after he becomes a party member, he could've been a great comic relief character.In conclusionProsGreat artstyleUnique musicInteresting settingJeromeHumour covers a diverse range of topics, seems to be based more on personal tastesExtremely cheapConsExtremely Monotonous gameplayHumour and writing seems forced at timesPlot doesn't make any sense, just a sequence of eventsPoor execution in general, wasted potentialNot enough JeromeAs a final point, other people seemed to have liked this game alot more, so it is quite possible you'll enjoy it more than me, plus the price is extremely low."
,Recommended,410670,22717182,"Posted: 29 April, 2016",all,Arishako,"The biggest drawback to this game, in my opinion, is the combat system. I'm a fan of turn-based combat in general, but this was terribly monotonous. This was mostly because it rarely seemed good to actually use your skills. The main character's regular attack quickly started doing about as much damage as his lowest cost offensive skill, and fights were generally over by the time I'd saved up enough TP for higher leveled ones. The first supporting character came with skills to attack all enemies at once, but the vast majority of the time I was fighting single opponents. Buffs and debuffs also felt to me like a waste of a turn in this game, although I might have just not had the right strategy. Most of the time, this wasn't too bad, but it made any area with random encounters feel like a pain just to slog through.The story is interesting enough to keep me engaged regardless of the combat. I'd say the writing can often be heavyhanded. There were times I got the impression that it was trying to hard to explain the joke/satire, which often ruined it. That said, there were also moments that worked really well and made me laugh, and also monsters that were unique. I'd recommend fans of RPGMaker-style games give it a shot."
,Recommended,410670,20553050,"Posted: 15 January, 2016",all,RenegadeQueen,For fans of Indie RPG's that like a little strangeness to their games. Definitely has replay value and for only a dollar that's plenty of gameplay time and weird story to absorb.
,Recommended,410670,20474987,"Posted: 11 January, 2016",all,Dare Evans,"So after completing everything there is to complete in this game, I can say that this was certainly worth the $0.65 that I paid for it, and I would recommend it at it's low price. Plus, I sold the trading card drops for $0.52, I believe? So, it was kind of only $0.13.That said, while the game has potential and charm, it's got plenty of very strange design choices and features that don't seem to work right. The most annoying of them being that interacting with objects takes place on the tiles around them, rather than the objects themselves. This means that unless you're standing in the right spot, nothing will happen when you search a crate, or look at something, which makes you think that nothing is supposed to happen. The art is pretty rough, but it's unique, at least. Anyone that avoids using RPG Maker's default assets deserves some credit. Soundtrack is wacky but enjoyable. Story is... something...One of the game's stronger points is probably it's use of references and humor. There were plenty of moments that I had a genuine laugh at.I've seen people imply that it's on the same level as LISA, and that's not even close to the truth, but I did enjoy my time with it. I'd definitely check out a sequel, as long as the price was kept as low as this was."
