,Not Recommended,410670,31520432,Posted: 3 May,all,Fauxy,"I think I would have given this a thumbs up under a lot of conditions. If it was less popular for example, I would be moved to have a bit of pity for creators who have obviously put in some effort and simply lacked creativity or talent in some regard. Or if it wasn't in a genre I've played so much of and have so much to compare it to, RPG maker games that seek to subvert classic RPG style storytelling. Or maybe if it had, as a comedy game, made me smile even once during the entirety of the four hours I gave it. Alas, none of those conditions are in effect.Suits: A Business RPGis just... not good.As a turn-based RPG it is a mediocrely designed, adds nothing new to the formula, random enemy grind where your first character does damage, your second character stuns the single member enemy parties you fight for 90% of the game, and you never bother with anything else because this combination kills everything in a slow and sure manner. Until you get a third character much too late in the game, at which point you can just keep spamming confirm to attack for every fight.As a story, this game is nothing but a vehicle for memes and pen15 jokes. If I had to explain to someone what lowest common denominator humor looked like, this game would be it. I suppose it grows some cliché anti-corporation popcorn and dead braincell plot towards the end, but that's all largely inconsequential in comparison to the game having a room full of popular Youtubers drawn as monsters, which I think is supposed to be funny? But there's no joke. It's literally just Youtubers with mildly stupid names based on their online personas. Because that in itself is funny right?How can I not compare this game to the likes ofLisa: The Painful RPG,OFF,Middens,Space Funeralor even (less relatedly)Undertale? It blatantly copies off the homework of the first two and still manages to fail the test. It certainly doesn't have the grounding in strong character and characterization based humor ofUndertale, or the benefit of having the backbone of a powerful thematic statement likeMiddensorLisa: The Painful RPG. It doesn't even manage to be as surreal as games likeOFForSpace Funeral, the games I care the least for of this ragtag bunch, because rather than creating a world and humor of its own it just riffs off of what's topical now and what might be completely forgotten in five years time. It doesn't even succeed at making any of that funny or compelling.And you can say, well, it's dirt cheap. Why have such high standards for it? Some of those games I'm comparing it to are FREE.This is a game where, it just seems like, the work is there but the creativity isn't. Sometimes that gap just can't be breached. It's not particularly polished but it's for the most part functional, and complete. It takes a lot of self deprecating stabs at itself and the devs' previous game, so I kind of feel like the devs weren't expecting the positive reviews? Again, there's something underdoggish about it that makes me want to pity it, but since so many people have already signed in favor of it, I might as well tell it like it is.It's not funny. It's not fun. It doesn't do anything interesting or say anything meaningful. The art is sloppy.  The fighting is tedious. The story is stupid. The overworld only lets you interact with boxes from certain directions. There is occasional lag. The game is using sound effects that come default with RPG Maker. The memes are not dank.TL;DR: No."
