,Recommended,410670,20962986,"Posted: 4 February, 2016",all,izzyheyo,"I bought this game because it was less than a buck and thought to myself, wow a decently priced game, I hope it's fun. Now I know the game is actually way too cheap.Suits: A Business RPG is one of those video games I'd recommend to anyone who thinks all indie games are just gimmicky, cash grabs with minimum effort put into them.A lot of attention went into this game, from the NPCs to the turn based fighting system; I can't find a fault with this game. The turn based fighting system is actually very fairly balanced, and never did I find myself thinking the game was too difficult or too easy. Even the black and white, doodlish style that might turn people off works in the game's favor. It perfectly reflects the bland, mass produced dystopia of a monopoly controlled world where even human life is treated as nothing more than capital gain or loss. It also has a very neat, brilliant ending I dare not spoil. These were some of my highlights.Cancelling that horrible showThe Big BangTheory, I mean, The Huge Boom HypothesisWent on an acid trip that taught me the meaning of lifeGot the Keys to SuccessFound a secret room full of shirtless menMet the very sexually attractive game devs whom were not falsely portayed in any way shape or form. Obviously. Only the most perfect men can create such a perfect game.Simply put, it's a fun game. Some reviews assert the game only mocks one topic and bashes it into the ground, but there is so much more to the humor than that.For example, every clock in the game reads either 4:20 or 7:30. You only find out why once you find a piece of paper in a cabinet on a left wing of a building detailing how scientists snuck something into the water supply so the populace would only see these two times. It was actually a very cleverly hidden joke making fun of conspiracy theorists on top of a 420 reference. Blaze it.I feel as long as you don't take anything too seriously and appreciate straightforward humor you'll enjoy the game for what it is."
