,Recommended,410670,20840497,"Posted: 29 January, 2016",all,AngelHalo,"I have to say that Technomancy Studios offers this game at a really modest price, and I can see why.The things I really enjoyed about this game is the overall presentation.  It's nice, unique, and I can appreciate the crudely drawn graphics and weird sound track.  Some may say that it draws parallels with OFF (a free game), and LISA (another steam game), and that wouldn't be too far from the truth, but not entirely correct either.  It ends up being its own unique experience from beginning to the end that is worth sitting through, along with its many comedic moments to break up the otherwise dark and demented atmosphere.With that said, there are problems I have with this game that is hard to complain about because of its value.  However, as I do appreciate the end product, I feel the need to address this in hopes to see improvement in the future.For one thing, the battle system may look like it has a decent amount of options, but there is hardly any strategy and variety involved.  Most of the special moves the protagonist can perform have a high miss chance (so I've noticed).  Even the move that lets him recharge his TP has a chance to not work at all, which I find ridiculous.  It gets to the point that his special abilities that he earns are just underminded entirely.  Once you recruit Jerome, the game just gets easy from there to where I just employed one strategy: attack with the Protagonist, use the staple move with Jerome to stun the enemy (or staple storm if there are multiple).  Once the enemy is stunned, keep spamming attack (or briefcase toss if possible), and repeat until I win.  Early on, you do have to manage your inventory, but any novice can catch on and abuse this strategy quickly.  Just remember to upgrade your equipment every now and then, have some healing items and water bottles for Jerome, and you never need to change up your strategy.  Once you recruit the third party member, the game just gets stupidly easy from there.  I'm not asking for anything complex, but I feel that the combat system really bogged down the overall experience for me.  It hurts that there is hardly any replay value.  I am aware that there is a hidden ending, but that involves getting the one item that you lose forever once you've completed half the game.  Some of the jokes presented at the end game felt forced too in retrospect.Should that steer your decision from buying the game?  Honestly, I cannot say.  The price does make the experience worth while over all despite the lack of replay value, and I still encourage you to at least give this game a try.  It won't take up too much of your time, and it costs about the same as a soda, and you don't have to worry about the excessive amounts of sugar and having to buy the soda again and again.Yeah, that was forced, but my point is, I would give this game a chance."
